 Description:
 The CV-22 is the Air Force Special Operations Forces (SOF) variant of the joint multi-mission V-22 tilt rotor aircraft. The CV-22 provides long-range, high-speed infiltration, exfiltration, personnel recovery, and
 resupply to Special Forces teams in hostile, denied, and politically sensitive areas. The Navy is the lead service for the Joint V-22 program. The Joint Program Manager is responsible for managing all variants of
 the V-22.

 Department of the Navy (DoN) funds the development of the MV-22 and CMV-22. The Air Force funds the service-common portion of the CV-22 while United States Special Operations Command (USSOCOM)
 funds the development and procurement of SOF peculiar systems. Each Service and Foreign Military Service participates in cost share for non-recurring engineering. The designed service life for the aircraft is
 10,000 flying hours over 30 years. Program of Record is 56 CV-22s.

 Funding for this exhibit is contained in PE 0401318F.

 Funding may be used to address Diminishing Manufacturing Source (DMS) and component obsolescence issues. This funding may include emerging modification requirements to support Program Support Costs
 (PSC), Advisory and Assistance Service (A&AS), system integration lab, trainers, equipment and other government cost.

 This program has associated RDT&E, AF funding in FY 2027 providing for systems engineering activities for Airframe Enhancements and Enhanced Self-Deployment Capabilities. Airframe Enhancements
 include but are not limited to the following: enhanced aircraft structures; rotor blade improvements; gearbox modifications; aircraft electro-mechanical hardware; durability/fatigue-life improvement; landing
 gear upgrades; fuel system improvements; and hydraulic system modifications. Enhanced Self-Deployment Capabilities include but are not limited to the following: improved ice protection; improved engine
 performance; navigation, communications, and battlespace situational awareness; electronic warfare; onboard weapon systems; defensive avionics systems and architecture; weight reduction initiatives; modular
 avionics; and cybersecurity measures. FY 2027 RDT&E, AF funding continues to fund these efforts.

 The FY 2026 spend plan amount for Aircraft Procurement includes $78,713 thousand of discretionary and $90,000 thousand of mandatory (reconciliation) for a total of $168,713.




