 Description:
 Air Traffic Control and Landing Systems (ATCALS) centrally manages the Air Force's Air Traffic Control (ATC) capability to ensure ATC facilities/equipment can safely and expeditiously support enroute and
 terminal operations in benign and combat areas of responsibility. Major ATCALS systems include, but are not limited to, tactical radars, tactical and fixed-base navigation aids (NAVAIDS), instrument landing
 systems, and air-to-ground communication radios.

 These systems enable air traffic controllers to provide advisory, sequencing, separation, and landing guidance services to all aircraft in assigned airspace. ATCALS must also be inter-operable with systems
 operated by other services, the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA), or host nations. When possible, contracts with other services or the FAA are used.

 In accordance with Section 1815 of the FY 2008 National Defense Authorization Act (P.L. 110-181), this item is necessary for use by the active and reserve components of the Armed Forces for homeland
 defense missions, domestic emergency responses, and providing military support to civil authorities.

 FY 2027 funding supports the programs below.

 1. ATCALS FIXED BASE (FB) NAVIGATIONAL AIDS (NAVAIDS) Family of Systems (FOS): This FOS includes Tactical Navigation (TACAN), Very High Frequency (VHF) Omnidirectional Ranging (VOR) and
 combined VOR and TACAN (VORTAC) systems as well as a remote maintenance and monitoring (RMM) capability. A total 121 systems are in operation at Continental United Stated (CONUS) and Outside the
 CONUS (OCONUS) bases. These systems provide aircraft with point-to-point navigation and airfield landing approach guidance and are critical to mission success in adverse weather conditions and Global
 Positioning System (GPS) denied operations. FY 2027 FB NAVAID FOS effort replace analog VORTACs with Doppler VORTACs at four Air Education and Training Command (AETC) bases and upgrade of
 the remote maintenance monitoring system analog dial up infrastructure to digital capability and compliance with the 2023 Department of War (DoW) Chief Information Officer (CIO) mandated analog-to-digital
 conversion. The DVORs are needed as analog VORs at these locations no longer provide reliable radials due to encroachment (powerlines and buildings). This results in increased pilot training costs and
 throughput times as instrument training must be conducted at alternate bases.

 2. FIXED BASE (FB) INSTRUMENT LANDING SYSTEM (ILS): FB-ILS consists of two subsystems which provide horizontal (localizer) and vertical (glide slope) guidance to enable aircraft to make an instrument
 precision approach to a runway in inclement weather. A total of seven FB-ILS systems will be procured. Six systems replace two end-of-life systems at Spangdahlem Air Base (AB) and four systems at Ramstein
 AB. One system will be installed on the new runway at Joint Reserve Base New Orleans.



