 Description:
 PE 0207429F:
 COMBAT TRAINING RANGES (CTR) program procures electronic telecommunication and instrumentation equipment and threat systems for training ranges worldwide to satisfy air combat and electronic warfare
 (EW) test and training capability requirements. It also procures range scoring systems and replacement equipment for electronics no longer logistically supportable. Funds may be used to address production
 Diminishing Manufacturing Sources and Material Shortage (DMSMS)/Obsolescence issues through studies, bridge buys, life of type buys, supplier parts replacement and qualification activities to preserve future
 production capabilities and capacities.

 ADVANCED RADAR THREAT SYSTEM VARIANT 1 (ARTS-V1): The ARTS-V1 program is comprised of dual long-range strategic Surface to Air Missile (SAM) threat systems. ARTS-V1 is designed to be used
 at Department of War (DoW) training ranges for aircrew training and tactics development to increase combat effectiveness and aircrew survivability. While various aircraft platforms may train against ARTS-
 V1, the focus of the program is to deliver realistic closed-loop threat replication meant to test 5th/6th generation aircraft capabilities against near-peer adversary capabilities. Funding will be used to support the
 installation, training, delivery, production, contractor support, sustainment buy-in, and retrofit of fielded articles.

 ADVANCED RADAR THREAT SYSTEM Variant 3 (ARTS- V3): ARTS-V3 is developing the most advanced ground-based radars in the US inventory using digital active electronically scanned radar technology
 that will be used to simulate the latest foreign peer adversary Surface-to-Air Missile (SAM) radar and Electronic Warfare (EW) threat systems. ARTS-V3 systems are a critical part of the Operational Training and
 Test Infrastructure (OTTI) plan for developing future Tactics, Techniques and Procedures (TTPs) for 5th/6th generation aircraft (F-35, B-21, F-47). ARTS-V3 systems are critical for the DoW's testing capabilities
 for validation of advanced airpower capabilities against threat-representative radar systems and validation of models used for the Joint Simulation Environment (JSE).

 ADVANCED RADAR THREAT SYSTEM TECH DEVELOPMENT: Procurement funds assigned to this element will be used to produce medium cost threat emitters/radars. Systems currently in consideration for
 production include the Combat Hazard Emitter for Engagement Training and Assessment (CHEETA), miniature radars from technology developed for ARTS V3, New Improved Near-peer Emitter Radar (NINER)
 and comparable technical alternatives. Funding will also be used to procure operational spares, engineering changes, and/or interim contract support.

 RADAR SIGNAL EMULATORS (RSE): The RSE program will procure advanced Surface-to-Air Missile (SAM) radar threat systems that can replicate multiple threats at the fidelity necessary for 5th generation
 and multi-domain training.




