 Description:
 PE 0305137F NATIONAL AIRSPACE SYSTEM (NAS)

 The NAS program modernizes and sustains the Department of War (DoW) Air Traffic Control (ATC) system in concert with the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA). NAS increases safety of flight, provides
 systems and facilities interoperable with FAA, replaces aging DoW ATC systems, provides identical service to military and civilian aircraft, and reduces DoW flight cancellations/delays and maintenance.

 NAS includes two programs: the ATC Voice Recorder Replacement (VRR) and the ATC Voice Switch Replacement (VSR).

 The ATC VRR replaces end-of-life Digital Audio Legal Recorder (DALR) that is no longer supported by the original equipment manufacturer. Recording of ATC controller-to-pilot and ATC tower communications
 is required to support accident investigations, near misses, runway incursions, etc. VRRs are in all Air Force ATC towers/Radar Approach Control (RAPCON) facilities. Replacement recorders are being procured
 though a Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) fixed-price contract with production options through FY 2030. The FAA will also be the lead agency for Operational Safety, Suitability and Effectiveness (OSS&E)
 and lifecycle support. An estimated 160 ATC VRRs will be procured through FY 2024-2030.

 The ATC VSR replaces the 25+ year old Enhanced Terminal Voice Switch (ETVS) systems which provide analog radio and telephone voice communications for ATC voice communications. These legacy, analog
 systems are experiencing multiple support issues and part constraints and do not meet the Department of War (DoW) Chief Information Officer (CIO) mandated transition to digital Internet Protocol (IP) capability.
 ATC controller-to-pilot communications are the heart of ATC capability and critical to safety of flight in the airfield terminal area. The FAA is also replacing ETVS voice switches and has awarded two contracts
 under their Brand New Air Traffic Control System program. These contracts to not include options for DoW. To ensure commonality and logistics support with the FAA, the Air Force will procure FAA certified
 ETVS replacement systems with the FAA vendors on separate contracts. A total of 150 VSRs are required.

 In accordance with Section 1815 of the FY 2008 National Defense Authorization Act (P.L. 110-181), these items are necessary for use by the active and reserve components of the Armed Forces for homeland
 defense missions, domestic emergency responses, and providing military support to civil authorities.

 Funding for this exhibit is contained in Program Element (PE) 0305137FRRs




