 Description:
 The Mission Planning Systems (MPS) Hardware program includes two main efforts; (1) in support of MPS software development and (2) in support of Precision Airdrop System (PADS) development sustainment,
 and modernization. The program equips U.S. Air Force (USAF) Active Duty, Air National Guard, and Air Force Reserve flying units with hardware required for mission planning and airdrop operations.

 1. MPS HARDWARE: Equips USAF operational flying units with hardware required to perform mission planning and integrate information with aircraft data transfer device systems. Aircraft supported include:

 Air Combat Command (ACC): F-15, F-16, F-22, F-35, A-10, E-3, E-4, E-7, RC/OC-135, HH-60, HC-130, EC-130, U-2, RQ-4, EA-37

 Air Mobility Command (AMC): C-5, C-17, C-130, KC-10, KC-135, KC-46

 Air Force Global Strike Command (AFGSC): B-1, B-2, B-21, B-52, UH-1

 Air Education and Training Command (AETC): T-38, T-7A, T-1, T-6

 MPS provides a mission data management system that seamlessly interfaces with other planning systems and aircraft avionics, offering a flexible, configurable, and cost-effective range of capabilities to meet
 peacetime, contingency, and wartime planning needs. Mission planning enables aircrews and planners to electronically receive mission information, such as tasking orders, intelligence data, target coordinates,
 imagery, and other relevant details from USAF Command, Control, Computers, Communications, Cyber, Intelligence, Surveillance, Reconnaissance, Position, Navigation, and Timing (C5ISRC-PNT) systems.
 The information is used to prepare mission plans that include data for equipment and personnel airdrop, weapons planning, maps, charts, imagery, flight logs, radar predictions, and navigation. The data is
 electronically transferred to the aircraft and/or precision-guided weapons. Streamlining mission planning and data transfer helps increase sortie rates, improve aircrew and aircraft survivability, and enhance
 aircrew readiness. This hardware and software combination enables aircrews and planners to plan safe and effective operational missions in a timely manner. As the mission planning enterprise modernizes into
 an open mission systems architecture, the program will provide end items that support enterprise infrastructure, software development, and deployment.

 The mission planning hardware includes essential equipment such as commercial-based personal computers (PCs), laptops, tablets, printers, storage devices, servers, displays, peripherals, software, software
 licenses, and support services. By leveraging technological advancements, the program enables high-end computing on smaller, mission-oriented devices that provide the necessary availability, survivability,
 processing power, and memory for modern mission planning. The design requirements balance performance with portability, ensuring the program evolves alongside software modernization efforts. These assets


