 Description:
 Mission Description:
 The Power Conditioning and Continuation Interfacing Equipment (PCCIE) program is critical to ensuring the quality, reliability, and continuity of electrical power supplied to essential Air Force systems. This
 program designs, develops, tests, and fields power conditioning and uninterruptible power supply (UPS) equipment necessary to support mission-critical assets such as communication systems, radar, data
 centers, hospitals, industrial processes, and command and control systems.
 The program replaces aging and legacy UPS units, ensuring operational resilience against electrical disturbances, outages, and environmental factors that compromise power integrity. As a multi-year effort, the
 PCCIE program addresses emergent requirements and supports ongoing modernization to meet growing demand and address legacy system obsolescence.
 Key Objectives:
 1. Power Quality Improvement: Reduces harmonic distortion, voltage fluctuations, and electrical disturbances.
 2. Operational Continuity: Provides uninterrupted power during outages or disturbances.
 3. Efficiency and Reliability: Optimizes power efficiency, minimizes energy losses, and extends mean time between failures (MTBF).
 4. UPS Modernization: Supports the transition to next-generation UPS systems, reducing maintenance costs and increasing system uptime.
 Program Components:
 • Power Conditioning Equipment: Procurement of voltage regulators, harmonic filters, and power factor correction devices.
 • Continuation Interfacing Equipment: UPS systems, transfer switches, and backup power systems.
 • Fielding and Installation: Deploys and installs UPS systems across Air Force bases, with flexibility for tailored installations to meet mission-specific needs.
 In accordance with Section 1815 of the FY 2008 National Defense Authorization Act (P.L. 110-181), this item is necessary for use by the active and reserve components of the Armed Forces for homeland
 defense missions, domestic emergency responses, and providing military support to civil authorities.
 • Program elements associated with this are: 27510F, 52834F, and 52844F.
 • Funding for this exhibit contained in PE 0207510F
